50|$|There {{is general}} {{agreement}} among cognitive scientists that <b>religion</b> <b>is</b> <b>an</b> outgrowth of brain architecture that evolved early in human history. However, there is disagreement {{on the exact}} mechanisms that drove {{the evolution of the}} religious mind. The two main schools of thought hold that either religion evolved due to natural selection and has selective advantage, or that <b>religion</b> <b>is</b> <b>an</b> evolutionary byproduct of other mental adaptations. Stephen Jay Gould, for example, believed that <b>religion</b> <b>was</b> <b>an</b> exaptation or a spandrel, in other words that religion evolved as byproduct of psychological mechanisms that evolved for other reasons.|$|R
